    <!-- Nephrotic syndrome information -->
    <string name="what_is_nephrotic">What is nephrotic syndrome?</string>
    <string name="nephrotic_definition">Nephrotic syndrome is a set of signs and symptoms indicating inflammation of the glomeruli (small filters in the kidneys). This condition affects the kidneys\' ability to remove waste and excess fluid from the body.</string>
    <string name="symptoms">Main symptoms</string>
    <string name="nephrotic_symptoms">• Hematuria (blood in urine)\n• Proteinuria (excess protein in urine)\n• Edema (swelling, especially in face, hands and feet)\n• High blood pressure\n• Reduced urine production\n• Fatigue and weakness</string>
    <string name="causes">Common causes</string>
    <string name="nephrotic_causes">• Infections (streptococcal, viral)\n• Autoimmune diseases (lupus, vasculitis)\n• Genetic diseases\n• Drugs and toxins\n• Systemic diseases (diabetes, amyloidosis)</string>
    <string name="treatment">Treatment</string>
    <string name="nephrotic_treatment">Treatment depends on the underlying cause:\n• Immunosuppressive medications\n• Corticosteroids\n• Blood pressure control\n• Salt and protein restriction in diet\n• Diuretics to control edema\n• Treatment of the causal disease</string>
    <string name="medical_warning">⚠️ Important: This information is educational. Always consult a doctor for proper diagnosis and treatment.</string>

    <!-- Postinfectious glomerulonephritis information -->
    <string name="what_is_glomerulonephritis">What is postinfectious glomerulonephritis?</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_definition">Postinfectious glomerulonephritis is a kidney disease that occurs after an infection, commonly bacterial. It is characterized by inflammation of the renal glomeruli due to an abnormal immune response against infectious antigens.</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_symptoms_title">Characteristic symptoms</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_symptoms">• Dark or tea-colored urine\n• Gross hematuria (visible blood in urine)\n• Facial and peripheral edema\n• High blood pressure\n• Reduced urine volume\n• Fatigue and general malaise\n• Previous fever (1-3 weeks before)</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_causes_title">Precipitating infections</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_causes">• Streptococcal infection (pharyngitis or scarlet fever)\n• Skin infections (impetigo)\n• Bacterial endocarditis\n• Pneumonia\n• Viral hepatitis\n• HIV\n• Meningococcemia</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_diagnosis_title">Diagnosis</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_diagnosis">• Urinalysis (hematuria, proteinuria)\n• Kidney function tests (creatinine, BUN)\n• Serum complement levels (C3, C4)\n• Antistreptolysin O antibodies (ASO)\n• Kidney biopsy in complex cases\n• Renal ultrasound</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_treatment_title">Treatment</string>
    <string name="glomerulonephritis_treatment">• Treatment of underlying infection\n• Blood pressure control\n• Salt and fluid restriction\n• Diuretics to manage edema\n• Corticosteroids in severe cases\n• Close monitoring of kidney function\n• Hospitalization in severe cases</string>

